-discovered-off-sicily" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/russia-ukraine-war-at-a-glance-what-we-know-on-day-532-of-the-invasion" target="_blank">Russia-Ukraine war at a glance: what we know on day 532 of the invasion</a></h2><div class="description"> Ukrainian forces attempt to cross the Dnieper River dividing liberated and occupied Kherson. At least 45 injured in blast outside Moscow, including six injured. Video shows explosion in Sergiyev Posad, north-east of Moscow, north of Moscow. Russian-imposed head of the occupied part of the region claimed the raid had been repelled.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 13:56:48 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/09/russia-ukraine-war-at-a-glance-what-we-know-on-day-532-of-the-invasion" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/dozens-of-secondhand-leopard-1-tanks-bought-by-eu-country-for-use-in-ukraine" target="_blank">EU country buys 49 secondhand Leopard tanks for Ukraine, arms dealer says</a></h2><div class="description"> Freddy Versluys says he has sold 49 tanks to another European government. He says it could be up to six months before they are on the battlefield in Ukraine. The tanks were bought by a major European country for the Ukrainian army fighting Russia, he said. He said he could not disclose the price of the sale of the tanks.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 21:06:59 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/dozens-of-secondhand-leopard-1-tanks-bought-by-eu-country-for-use-in-ukraine" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ruzzki-not-welcome-the-russian-exiles-getting-a-hostile-reception-in-georgia" target="_blank">‘Ruzzki not welcome’: the Russian exiles getting a hostile reception in Georgia</a></h2><div class="description"> After the invasion of Ukraine, thousands of Russians fled to Tbilisi, Georgia. But the graffiti that has sprung up across the city suggests not everyone is pleased to see them. “I went from a place I didn't feel at home to a place that is not welcoming me”</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 04:00:03 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/aug/08/ruzzki-not-welcome-the-russian-exiles-getting-a-hostile-reception-in-georgia" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/09/no-swearing-no-singing-no-fancy-dress-uks-strictest-pub-calls-time" target="_blank">No swearing, no singing, no fancy dress: UK’s ‘strictest pub’ calls time</a></h2><div class="description"> Landlord Shaun Collinge has run the York pub for 31 years and says the rules are harder to enforce post-pandemic. Rules include: no swearing, no singing, no television, no music, no stag parties, no hen dos and no fancy dress.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 12:55:28 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/09/no-swearing-no-singing-no-fancy-dress-uks-strictest-pub-calls-time" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2023/aug/09/apple-maps-cycling-transport-google" target="_blank">A decade after a disastrous launch, is Apple Maps finally good?</a></h2><div class="description"> Engineers’ work on cycling and public transit have transformed the app – but rural directions remain a sticking point. In October 2022, New York City officials unveiled a new bike lane on Schermerhorn street, one of the most dangerous and heavily trafficked streets in downtown Brooklyn. For Apple to know the lane was open, it had to have updates from the Adams administration.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 10:00:22 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">tech</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2023/aug/09/apple-maps-cycling-transport-google" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/09/people-would-have-lost-their-culture-the-birmingham-record-label-that-saved-south-asian-music" target="_blank">‘People would have lost their culture’: the Birmingham record label that saved south Asian music</a></h2><div class="description"> Muhammad Ayyub moved to Birmingham from Pakistan from Gujrat in 1961. The 84-year-old opened a shop selling transistor radios on Balsall Heath Road in 1966. Oriental Star Agencies championed legends such as Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan and nurtured bhangra.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 14:05:24 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/09/people-would-have-lost-their-culture-the-birmingham-record-label-that-saved-south-asian-music" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/09/3967-steps-a-day-the-new-magic-number-for-a-healthy-happy-life" target="_blank">3,967 steps a day: the new magic number for a healthy, happy life?</a></h2><div class="description"> The very thought of exercise can be tiring, but don't despair. Small changes can make a big difference to your body. Walking has been around 300m to 400m years since our ancestors replaced fins and gills with legs. It is thought that our ancestors have been walking for 300m years.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 14:05:18 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2023/aug/09/3967-steps-a-day-the-new-magic-number-for-a-healthy-happy-life" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/aug/09/mushroom-mystery-family-lunch-leaves-australian-town-reeling-after-three-die-in-suspected-poisoning" target="_blank">Mushroom mystery: family lunch leaves Australian town reeling after three deaths in suspected poisoning</a></h2><div class="description"> Police investigating what looks like a fatal case of food poisoning in Leongatha in eastern Victoria. Locals recall the victims as kind and community-spirited. Four of the guests began feeling very unwell and eventually sought treatment at local hospitals. Police are investigating what appears to be a fatal food poisoning.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 12:02:35 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/aug/09/mushroom-mystery-family-lunch-leaves-australian-town-reeling-after-three-die-in-suspected-poisoning" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/09/female-experience-inside-taylor-swift-club-night-sweeping-the-uk" target="_blank">‘I love being part of a collective female experience’: inside the all-Taylor Swift club night sweeping the UK</a></h2><div class="description"> Swiftogeddon began as a novelty one-off but it’s now a weekly sellout event where strangers become best pals and every song is greeted as if it were the greatest ever written. The club night is now a UK-wide phenomenon and has snowballed into a national phenomenon.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 07:12:40 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2023/aug/09/female-experience-inside-taylor-swift-club-night-sweeping-the-uk" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/09/on-our-doorstep-review-extraordinary-story-of-volunteers-in-the-calais-jungle" target="_blank">On Our Doorstep review – extraordinary story of volunteers in the Calais Jungle</a></h2><div class="description"> Thomas Laurance’s documentary focuses on the British activists who arrived in the refugee camp with housing materials and other life-saving supplies. The documentary observes the cultural vibrancy and solidarity that blossomed on the muddy ground. The Calais Jungle was home to thousands of refugees and migrants hoping to either claim asylum in France or obtain a passage to the UK.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 12:00:24 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/film/2023/aug/09/on-our-doorstep-review-extraordinary-story-of-volunteers-in-the-calais-jungle" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/09/luminous-keepers-and-a-nod-to-andy-gray-the-2023-24-premier-league-kits" target="_blank">Luminous keepers and a nod to Andy Gray: the 2023-24 Premier League kits</a></h2><div class="description"> The Premier League season kicks off this week with the rolling out of new kits. From Arsenal's commemorative fail to Spurs' handsome home strip that would not look amiss at Wimbledon, here's the latest on the season's sartorial winners and losers. We take a look at who’s sartorially winning this year, and who has scored a fashion own goal.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 07:00:06 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/09/luminous-keepers-and-a-nod-to-andy-gray-the-2023-24-premier-league-kits" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/labour-win-power-party-strategy-ideas" target="_blank">This narrow, win-at-all-costs strategy could take Labour to victory, but not to power |  Neal Lawson</a></h2><div class="description"> Neal Lawson is director of the cross-party campaign organisation Compass. He knows that without bold, transformative ideas, success will simply tie the party’s hands. He says the plan was not to win but to snatch the party back under the temporary cloak of Corbynism-without-Corbyn.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 11:05:42 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/labour-win-power-party-strategy-ideas" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/lee-anderson-migrant-politics-margaret-thatcher-rishi-sunak" target="_blank">Lee Anderson’s vile anti-migrant comments pose this question: do we want politics like this? | Hugh Muir</a></h2><div class="description"> Lee Anderson, the deputy chair of the Conservative party, says asylum seekers should 'f*** off back to France' Even Thatcher’s governments were above the hateful, toxic rhetoric now being favoured by Sunak and his lieutenants. He was speaking to the Daily Express, with the knowledge that this once-great British newspaper now thrives on printing such things.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 12:21:20 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/lee-anderson-migrant-politics-margaret-thatcher-rishi-sunak" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/female-andrew-tate-influencer-dating-debt-man-bills" target="_blank">‘The female Andrew Tate’: the new influencer dating doctrine is extreme – but I can see why it’s popular | Kimberly McIntosh</a></h2><div class="description"> Young women struggling with debt and burnout need a better vision than getting a rich man to pay the bills. The way to get wealthy men to buy you drinks is to go to high-end bars alone before the after-work rush. SheraSeven, the self-styled ‘financial adviser’ whose advice I had inadvertently followed, says Shera.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 09:00:21 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/female-andrew-tate-influencer-dating-debt-man-bills" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/immersive-van-gogh-art-disney-lighthouse" target="_blank">So long ‘immersive Van Gogh’: we deserve better than this cynical and elitist approach to art | Rachel Connolly</a></h2><div class="description"> Disney’s Lighthouse Immersive puts on shows in which reproductions of work by household-name artists are blown up and projected on to the walls of galleries. Music is piped into the space to curate the mood, taking the place that imagination plays in a traditional exhibition. We never needed gizmos and expensive tickets to enjoy great art.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 13:26:41 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/immersive-van-gogh-art-disney-lighthouse" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/andrew-malkinson-was-right-to-expose-these-ministers-why-do-they-keep-punishing-innocent-people" target="_blank">Andrew Malkinson was right to expose these ministers. Why do they keep punishing innocent people? | Matt Foot</a></h2><div class="description"> Andrew Malkinson is right to raise the plight of miscarriage of justice victims. The state has recouped the cost of board and lodgings from compensation given to some victims of miscarriages of justice. The innocent have paid for the pleasure of living at their majesty’s pleasure.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 07:00:08 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/andrew-malkinson-was-right-to-expose-these-ministers-why-do-they-keep-punishing-innocent-people" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/britain-conservatives-government-bibby-stockholm" target="_blank">Britain is trapped in political purgatory – waiting for its undead government to fall | Rafael Behr</a></h2><div class="description"> Policy that can’t work and laws written purely for campaign slogans are clear symptoms of a moribund regime. Residents on board the Bibby Stockholm, the barge moored in Dorset to house asylum claimants, are classified by the Home Office as “non-detained” persons.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 05:00:04 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/britain-conservatives-government-bibby-stockholm" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/scientific-misconduct-retraction-watch" target="_blank">There’s far more scientific fraud than anyone wants to admit | Ivan Oransky and Adam Marcus</a></h2><div class="description"> Stanford president Marc Tessier-Lavigne resigned last month after a series of investigations exposed serious problems in his research. In June it was revealed that a scholar at Harvard Business school, Francesca Gino, was accused of having falsified research about honesty. Despite recent scandals of research misconduct and error, the academic world still seems determined to look the other way.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 10:07:22 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/scientific-misconduct-retraction-watch" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/looking-for-your-next-adventure-why-not-move-to-venus" target="_blank">Looking for your next adventure? Why not move to Venus? | Arwa Mahdawi</a></h2><div class="description"> Guillermo Söhnlein wants to send 1,000 people to Venus's atmosphere by 2050. He co-founded the submersibles company OceanGate, which went down 10 years ago. He has concluded that getting to Venus is ‘very doable’ - it’s just like a caravan holiday!</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 10:00:22 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/09/looking-for-your-next-adventure-why-not-move-to-venus" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/the-guardian-view-on-language-apps-a-reminder-that-millions-aspire-to-be-mutilingual" target="_blank">The Guardian view on language apps: a reminder that millions aspire to be mutilingual | Editorial</a></h2><div class="description"> Monty Python's Life of Brian is a classic grammar gag in their 1979 film Life ofBrian. The joke’s appeal depends partly on its slide from totalitarian horror into a fear of traditional language teaching. Learning by rote and punishment by writing lines have featured in Tory prescriptions for a cure to educational ills.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 17:52:39 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">entertainment</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/aug/08/the-guardian-view-on-language-apps-a-reminder-that-millions-aspire-to-be-mutilingual" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/foreign-aid-cuts-are-a-disaster-for-women" target="_blank">Foreign aid cuts are a disaster for women | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Prof Geeta Nargund: UK aid budget cuts are ‘death sentence’ for world’s most vulnerable children. In Afghanistan, for example, maternal mortality rates are already three times higher than the global average. For every 100,000 live births in Afghanistan, 620 women die.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:32:34 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/aug/08/foreign-aid-cuts-are-a-disaster-for-women" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/left-in-limbo-by-brexit-safety-mark-chaos" target="_blank">Left in limbo by Brexit safety mark chaos | Letters</a></h2><div class="description"> Uncertainty over Britain’s post-Brexit version of the CE mark has hampered development of medical devices, says Roger Bayston. Scientists need to partner with manufacturers in order to get these devices out of the lab and into the clinic. They say industrial partners have pulled out of agreements because it has been too costly to embark on double certification of potential products.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 15:32:11 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">world</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/aug/08/left-in-limbo-by-brexit-safety-mark-chaos" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/09/womens-world-cup-2023-last-16-power-rankings-england-france-australia-usa" target="_blank">Women’s World Cup power rankings: France on the rise, England drop down</a></h2><div class="description"> Japan continue to look the most in-form team in the competition. France, Australia, Spain and Colombia are all making upward moves. Hinata Miyazawa remains top scorer with five goals, equalling Homare Sawa’s Golden Boot-winning total in 2011.</div><br><span class="date"><strong>Published on:</strong> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 12:19:45 GMT</span><br><div class="category"><strong>Category: </strong><span class="category-text">sports</span></div><br><div class="source"><strong>Source: </strong><span class="source-text">The Guardian</span></div><br><div class="link"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/09/womens-world-cup-2023-last-16-power-rankings-england-france-australia-usa" target="_blank">Click here to read the full article</a></div><br></div><hr><div class='item'><h2><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/09/lucy-bronze-england-unhappy-performances-womens-world-cup-colombia" target="_blank">Lucy Bronze admits England unhappy with performances and ‘can give more’</a></h2><div class="description"> England face Colombia in the World Cup quarter-final on 